#### Getting and preparing Data ####
NIMP provides yearly state legislative donation data. This process has changed overtime, but they are very willing to work with scholars. You will need data that provides either aggregate yearly donations from each group to each candidate or every donation. This is the process at it stands in April of 2019.

1) Create an account with Followthemoney.org Then fill out the exemption form to get expanded academic access from them. (The exemption form is in your account settings. Click on 'Download Limits' in the User Options box, and then the "apply for free expanded access" link at the end of the first paragraph. Fill out and send the form in, and NIMP will get to you right away)

2) The best way to download the data is by election year. This link: https://www.followthemoney.org/show-me?dt=1&y=2001&c-exi=1&c-r-ot=H&d-et=3#[{1|gro=c-t-id,d-id will bring you to the data for the 2001 election. To download the data scroll to the bottom of the page and click the CSV link. Follow the prompts. Note: The following options should be checked: Records, and Candidates. In addition the top should be "Q: Show me Non-Individuals' contributions to State House/Assembly Candidates in elections in 2001 (within federal, state and local data)" (so you will get just non-individuals and state leg candidates)

3) To download all the data you will just have to switch out 2001 with other years.

4) The scripts that follow assume you've saved each year as: FollowTheMoneyDownloadXXXX.csv where XXXX is the full year (2001 for example).

fields.value: Replication Data for: Mapping Influence: Partisan Networks Across the United States, 2000 to 2016

dsDescriptionValue.value: The parties as networks approach has become a critical component of understanding American political parties. Research on it has so far mainly focused on variation in the placement of candidates within a network at the national level. This is impart due to a lack of data on state level party networks.  In this article I fill that gap by developing state party networks for 47 states from 2000 to 2016 using candidate donation data. To do this I introduce a backboning network analysis method not yet used in political science to infer relationships among donors at the state level. Finally I validate these state networks and then show how parties have varied across states and over time. The networks developed here will be made publicly available for future research. Being able to quantify variation in party network structure will be important for understanding variation in party-policy linkages at the state level.

publicationCitation.value: Reuning, Kevin. [date]. “Mapping Influence: Partisan Networks Across the United States, 2000 to 2016.” State Politics & Policy Quarterly Forthcoming. http://spa.sagepub.com/

This dataset underwent an independent verification process that replicated the tables and figures in the primary article. For the supplementary materials, verification was performed solely for the successful execution of code. The verification process was carried out by the Odum Institute for Research in Social Science at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

Data for the backboning process for this manuscript are not available on the AJPS Dataverse due to the terms of use of the data producer. To request access to these data please see the Terms of Use for this record.
